turn.0: Hi, I'm your automated assistant. I can answer your questions about Red-necked wallaby.
turn.1: Where do the red-necked wallabies live?
turn.2: They have adapted to living in proximity to humans and can be found grazing on lawns in the fringes of Hobart and other urban areas.
turn.3: Are there any other interesting aspects about this article?
turn.4: The mainland form, "Macropus rufogriseus banksianus", breeds all year round. Captive animals maintain their breeding schedules; Tasmanian females that become pregnant out of their normal season delay birth until summer, which can be anything up to eight months later.
turn.5: Do they have any other habitats?
turn.6: There are significant introduced populations in the Canterbury region of New Zealand's South Island.
turn.8: In 1870, several wallabies were transported from Tasmania to Christchurch, New Zealand.
turn.9: Were they released into the wild?
turn.10: Two females and one male from this stock were later released about Te Waimate, the property of Waimate's first European settler Michael Studholme.
turn.12: The year 1874 saw them freed in the Hunters Hills, where over the years their population has dramatically increased.
